# Processing data:
rm(list = ls())
# Read in data from Final Project Code.Rmd
bmw <- read.csv("~/BMWpricing_trainingvalidation.csv",
    as.is = T)

# Split data into training and validation sets:
DataSetTraining = bmw %>%
    filter(bmw$training == 1)  # 50% of the data
DataSetValidation = bmw %>%
    filter(bmw$validation == 1)  # 50% of the data

# Convert all continuous variables to numeric:
DataSetTraining$mileage <- as.numeric(DataSetTraining$mileage)
DataSetTraining$engine_power <- as.numeric(DataSetTraining$engine_power)
DataSetTraining$price <- as.numeric(DataSetTraining$price)
# Filter out implausible observations:
DataSetTraining <- DataSetTraining %>%
    filter(mileage >= 0, )
DataSetTraining <- DataSetTraining %>%
    filter(engine_power > 0)

# Calculate the interval between sold and
# registration dates:
training.regis <- strptime(DataSetTraining$registration_date,
    "%m/%d/%Y")
training.sold <- strptime(DataSetTraining$sold_at,
    "%m/%d/%Y")
# Create age variable (in days)
DataSetTraining$age <- difftime(training.sold, training.regis,
    units = "days")
DataSetTraining$age <- as.numeric(DataSetTraining$age)

# Convert all the categorical variables to
# factors:
colnames(DataSetTraining)
##  [1] "X"                 "maker_key"         "model_key"        
##  [4] "mileage"           "engine_power"      "registration_date"
##  [7] "fuel"              "paint_color"       "car_type"         
## [10] "feature_1"         "feature_2"         "feature_3"        
## [13] "feature_4"         "feature_5"         "feature_6"        
## [16] "feature_7"         "feature_8"         "price"            
## [19] "sold_at"           "training"          "validation"       
## [22] "age"
categorical.colnames <- colnames(DataSetTraining)[c(2:3,
    6:16)]
for (.col in categorical.colnames) {
    DataSetTraining[, .col] <- factor(DataSetTraining[,
        .col], ordered = F)
}

attach(DataSetTraining)

# Approach 2: Residuals Fitting WLS regression
# with transformed variables: Residual:
residualweight = residuals(m.trans)
# Absolute value of residual:
absresidualweight = abs(residuals(m.trans))
# Creating weight data frame:
attach(DataSetTraining)
## The following objects are masked from DataSetTraining (pos = 3):
## 
##     age, car_type, engine_power, feature_1, feature_2, feature_3,
##     feature_4, feature_5, feature_6, feature_7, feature_8, fuel,
##     maker_key, mileage, model_key, paint_color, price,
##     registration_date, sold_at, training, validation, X
dataweight = data.frame(log(age), residualweight, absresidualweight)
# Creating Plot for Residuals:
plot1 <- ggplot(dataweight, aes(x = log(age), y = residualweight)) +
    geom_point(size = 0.1) + ggtitle("Residuals")
# Creating Plot for Abs. Residuals:
plot2 <- ggplot(dataweight, aes(x = log(age), y = absresidualweight)) +
    geom_point(size = 0.1) + ggtitle("Absolute Residuals")
# Plotting:
grid.arrange(plot1, plot2, ncol = 2)

# Calculate fitted values from a regression of
# absolute residuals vs log(age)
DataSetTraining$age <- log(DataSetTraining$age)
my.weights2 <- 1/fitted(lm(abs(residuals(m.trans)) ~
    age))^2
# Approach 1: Variance Fitting WLS regression
# with transformed variables: Best predicator
# chosen to be log(age) based on regression
# coefficients; to be confirmed with LASSO
# Getting standard deviation:
sdprice.by.log.age <- by(price, log(age), sd)
# Getting mean:'
mprice.by.log.age <- by(price, log(age), mean)
# Plotting SD Price vs. Mean log(age):
plot(mprice.by.log.age, sdprice.by.log.age, xlab = "Log(age)",
    ylab = "SD of Price", main = "SD Price versus log(age) mean; LOESS fit",
    col = "red", lty = 0, cex = 1, pch = 19)
# LOESS:
smooth.sd <- loess.smooth(mprice.by.log.age, sdprice.by.log.age)
# Plot LOESS regressor:
lines(smooth.sd, lty = 2)

# Let's use the LOESS fit to create weights for
# WLS regression: Create LOESS object:
smooth.pricesd.orig <- loess(sdprice.by.log.age ~ mprice.by.log.age,
    control = loess.control(surface = "direct"))
# Predict SD LOESS interpolant:
sdprice.fits <- predict(smooth.pricesd.orig, data.frame(mprice.by.log.age = log(age)))
my.weights1 <- 1/(sdprice.fits)^2

age_s = scale(log(age))

mileage_s = scale(sqrt(mileage))

x.df <- model.matrix(lm(sqrt(price) ~ mileage_s + age_s +
    engine_power_s + model_key + car_type + I(age_s *
    mileage_s) + feature_1 + feature_2 + feature_3 +
    feature_4 + feature_5 + feature_6 + feature_8,
    weights = my.weights2))

    nfolds = 5)
